21/01/2007
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- The launch of EU membership talks with Macedonia will be one of the priorities of the future Slovenian presidency of the EU, due in the first half of 2008, Slovenian Foreign Minister Dimitrij Rupel confirmed during a visit to Skopje on Friday (January 19th). 
A similar statement was made by Slovenian Prime Minister Janez Jansa at the European Parliament earlier this week.
During talks with his Macedonian counterpart Antonio Milososki on Friday, Rupel voiced confidence that Macedonia was capable of fulfilling the EU requirements. 
He called on the country to speed up the implementation of reforms, promising that Ljubljana stood ready to provide its expertise and experience. 
Rupel also held talks on Friday with Macedonian President Branko Crvenkovski and Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski. 
(Dnevnik, Vecer, Utrinski Vesnik - 20/01/07; Makfax, Telma TV - 19/01/07)
